This wiki makes a brief introduction how a Tableau Desktop user should publish their dashboard to Tableau Server. This document also lists some of the rules while creating dashboards for the client service.
# Database Selection

While you start developing dashboard or a report from your Tableau Desktop you need to select a data source. *Please see your database administrator to learn what database to use.*You will need to authorize to selected database, your database administrator should login for you. For our customers a user defined with limited rights on selected database. After you login to database you would be able to process your queries.If you would need to use a SP or function for your dashboard you can cooperate with database administrator in order to create SP or function on the database. Connection type will be "Extract" at the moment. In case of "Live" connection need, you need to sync with your database administrator.
## Design of Dashboard

of "Live" connection need, you need to sync with your database administrator.
## Design of Dashboard

This is a process you need to handle after data connection. Create the reports and dashboards as you will.There are some rules we need to follow.- There shouldn't be any wild chars on the Workbook or Dashboard. Only alphanumeric chars and space should be used. If Workbook name has more than one word we should use space between words.

- Workbook names should be tidy, if there are more than one word we should use upper case for each word.

# Publishing

When you are done with creating dashboard. In order to publish, please connect with tableau server administrator. We should publish workbooks for the customer site as administrator to handle user rights and permissions for published workbooks.
# Post-Publishing Process

When publishing the dashboard process finished, database administrator should handle the permissions for published workbook.

# How to create a new site for customer

It is pretty straight forward to create a new site to publish dashboards for your customers inside a isolated site instead of publishing them inside Tableau default site. Creating a site for your customer will provide you to manage dashboards for your customers inside the site and you can manage multiple customers at different Tableau sites. It will also provide you separate customer information and will prevent not to publish different customers info in other customer page.

- Enter the Tableau server url onto your browsers address bar. Enter login credentials and select default site after you login. (It is not mandatory to select default site, admin can switch between pages but in first login attempt there will be no sites and it will automatically login to default site)

- After login user selected the default site he will see default page as below:

- After admin user logged into system he should click on the "Admin" button at the left of the page. It will open the maintenance page which a user can see the status of Tableau server.

- When you are inside the administration page, click on the "Site" at the left navigation bar. Then click on "Add" button when the site page appears.

- After you press add, Tableau will prompt a pop-up you to name your new site

You should enter the required information for your new site. For our customers we directly give their names to make it easy like 'Mavi', 'Penti', 'Koton' etc. After you create your site for your customer site direct link of the site will be like [http://tableserverurl/t/SiteName.](http://tableserverurl/t/SiteName.)

### Enable Trusted Authentication

- Open a command prompt with administrator rights.

- Go into "Program Files\Tableau\Tableau Server\9.2\bin"

- Stop tableau server: tabadmin stop

- Enable REST API : tabadmin set wgserver.trusted_hosts "<trusted IP addresses or host names>"

- Propagate the change: tabadmin config

- Start Tableau server: tabadmin start

As of 16.01.2016, we use the InventService user to render reports in Maps UI, rather than the inventtableauadmin user which has full Admin privileges in Tableau.

With this new change, we need to specify the Tableau SiteId of the customer in the Maps.UI configuration. This SiteId can only be obtained over the REST API. I wrote a simple [LinqPad](https://invent.atlassian.net/wiki/display/DEV/LINQPad) script to obtain all sites defined in Tableau. The script uses the inventtableauadmin user to use the [Query Sites](https://onlinehelp.tableau.com/current/api/rest_api/en-us/REST/rest_api_ref.htm#Query_Sites)endpoint of the Tableau REST API and get all defined sites. The script requires the password of inventtableauadmin. This password can be obtained from LastPass, or from  or Onur Dündar. The LinqPad script is attached to this page.
